```
LOADING dreamsim.exe...
parsing dream fragment: "dad was writing condolences on a transparent, bubble wrapped coffin"
generating world state...

================================================================================
DREAM SIMULATION INITIALIZED
================================================================================

You stand in a vast concrete hall with crumbling pillars. Paint flakes from the ceiling like dead skin. At the far end, a blue tunnel pulses with uncertain light - each pulse makes the walls breathe.

In the center of the room: a coffin made entirely of bubble wrap, stretched taut like a membrane. You can see through it - there's nothing inside but more layers of bubbles, going deeper than should be possible.

Your father kneels beside it, writing with a black marker directly onto the bubbles. Each word makes a soft *pop* as the ink settles. The words blur and reform:

"SORRY FOR YOUR LOSS"
becomes
"SORRY FOR YOUR"
becomes
"SORRY FOR"
becomes
"SORRY"

He doesn't look up. His hand keeps moving even when the marker runs dry, scratching invisible condolences into the air.

The blue tunnel at the room's end hums. Something moves in its depths.

  - examine [object]
  - approach [father/coffin/tunnel]
  - speak [words]
  - listen
  - pop [bubbles]
  - walk [direction]

>
```

```
APPROACHING: father
================================================================================

You move across the debris-strewn floor. Your footsteps echo wrong - each step arrives before you take it.

As you get closer, you notice:

- His hands are stained black from the marker, but the stains form patterns like constellations
- He's younger than he should be, or older, it keeps changing with each blink
- The marker squeaks against the bubble wrap: *squeak-pop-squeak-pop*
- He's humming something familiar but backwards

You're standing right beside him now. This close, you can see through the coffin better - there ARE layers inside, infinite recursive bubbles, and in each bubble: a tiny reflection of this same room, with a tiny dad writing on a tinier coffin.

Without looking up, he speaks:

"They need to know someone's sorry. Even if they're not here. Especially if they're not here."

His hand keeps moving. The words he's writing now say:
"HELLO FROM THE OTHER SIDE OF THE GLASS"

But when you blink, they say:
"DON'T FORGET TO BREATHE"

The blue tunnel behind you inhales. The room tilts slightly.

A bubble pops by itself. The sound is too loud. Inside where it popped: a small photo of Harry, surfing.

> Available actions:
  - speak "___" [to father]
  - read [all messages on coffin]
  - touch [father's shoulder]
  - look [into father's eyes]
  - pop [bubble with photo]
  - examine [the marker]
  - ask "who is this for?"

>
```

```
LOOKING: into father's eyes
================================================================================

You lean down to meet his gaze. He lifts his head slowly, like it weighs more than it should.

His eyes are:
- Red-rimmed (from the weed? from crying? from not existing properly?)
- The whites are actually tiny bubble wrap, thousands of miniature spheres
- Each pupil contains a small movie theater playing different films simultaneously

In the left eye: Harry on the train tracks, rewinding and playing, rewinding and playing
In the right eye: A whale the size of a hotel, breathing its last breath

"Oh, it's you," he says, and his voice comes from somewhere deeper than his throat. "I've been writing these for hours. Or years? The marker never runs out if you believe hard enough."

He blinks. 

When his eyes open again, they're completely normal. Brown. Tired. Human.

"I can't remember who died," he whispers. "But someone needs to know we're sorry. Someone always needs to know we're sorry."

A tear rolls down his cheek. When it hits the bubble wrap, it spreads like ink, forming words:
"$3000 A DAY BUT AT WHAT COST"

Behind you, the blue tunnel makes a sound like someone inhaling through water.

The photo of Harry in the popped bubble starts moving - he's paddling out, over and over, never reaching the wave.

> Available actions:
  - speak "___" 
  - wipe [his tears]
  - tell him ["who died" / "it's okay" / "Harry is here"]
  - share [a memory]
  - pop [the Harry bubble completely]
  - turn [toward blue tunnel]
  - hug [father]

>
```

```
ASKING: father - "why $3000 a day"
================================================================================

His hand stops mid-letter. The marker hovers over a bubble that reads "WE TRIED OUR BE"

He looks at you, confused for a moment, like you've asked him to explain water to a fish.

"The bears," he says simply. "Don't you remember?"

The room shifts. For a second, you smell marijuana, thick and pungent. The concrete pillars become trees. Pine? The blue tunnel flickers into a massive hollow tree trunk.

"Three thousand dollars a day selling weed. All they had to do was fetch it from the bears. The bears would bring the packages down from the mountain. Perfect system."

He draws a small bear on one of the bubbles. It starts moving, carrying a tiny package.

"But Harry wanted to surf instead."

The marker slips. Writes by itself: "SOME WAVES YOU CAN'T CATCH TWICE"

"That's why I'm writing these apologies," he continues, looking back down at the transparent coffin. "For everyone who chose the money over the waves. For everyone who chose the waves over the money. For the bears who are still waiting on the mountain."

A bubble pops. Inside: a tiny glass hotel, built from the skeleton of something enormous.

"The whale penis hotel only made $2000 a day, you know. The bears were better business."

The blue tunnel exhales. It sounds like the ocean. Or like something drowning in the ocean.

> Available actions:
  - ask "what happened to the bears?"
  - ask "is this Harry's coffin?"
  - tell him "Harry came back"
  - pop [the bear bubble]
  - examine [the whale hotel bubble]
  - listen [to the tunnel]
  - speak "the waves were worth it"

>
```

```
ENTERING: whale hotel
================================================================================

The bubble containing the whale hotel expands around you. Reality inverts. You're inside now.

The lobby is vast - ribcage architecture, each beam a single curved bone reaching up five stories. The floor is polished baleen, dark and striated. Everything smells like salt and ancient ocean.

At the reception desk: your father, younger, wearing a suit made of seaweed. He's checking in guests who aren't there, sliding keycards into empty air.

"Room 333," he says to no one. "The blowhole suite. Excellent view of nothing."

The walls breathe. Literally. In. Out. In. Out.

You notice:
- Elevator shafts that are actually arteries, pulsing red light upward
- A bar made from a single vertebra, bottles of amber liquid lined up
- Harry's surfboard leaning against what might be the whale's heart, calcified into marble
- A guest registry on the desk, all the names are "SORRY FOR YOUR LOSS"
- Windows that look out onto deep ocean, despite being on land
- The sound of $2000 being counted, over and over, somewhere in the walls

Your father (the hotel version) looks up: "Oh good, you're here. The bears called. They want to know why we switched from mountains to ocean. I told them the profit margins are worse but the view is better."

Behind the desk, a small plaque:
"BUILT FROM GRIEF
ONE PENIS AT A TIME
EST. WHENEVER HARRY STOPPED SURFING"

The coffin room is visible through the whale's eye socket, a tiny diorama where your other father still writes.

> Available actions:
  - check in [to room]
  - examine [guest registry]
  - approach [Harry's surfboard]
  - drink [at vertebra bar]
  - ride [artery elevator]
  - ask "who stays here?"
  - touch [the breathing walls]
  - exit [through blowhole/eye/mouth]

>
```
